---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ResetData from '@components/ResetData.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About & intention" description="Why this companion exists, its faithfulness principles, and the copyright disclaimer.">
  <article class="wrap prose">
    <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
    <h1 class="glow-title">Intention &amp; principles</h1>

    <p>
      This site is an independent <strong>companion and study aid</strong> for
      <em>Lem’alar</em> (“The Flashes”), one of the books of the Risale-i Nur
      collection by Bediüzzaman Said Nursî. It is built for English-speaking
      readers who want to understand, navigate, search and remember this dense
      work.
    </p>

    <p>
      It is <strong>not the book.</strong> We do not host or reproduce the
      Risale-i Nur text or any of its translations. The actual reading happens on
      the official source, <a href="https://www.erisale.com/?locale=en" rel="noopener" target="_blank">erisale.com</a>,
      which we link to throughout. What you find here is the map around the
      original: outlines, our own summaries, a glossary, a concept index, search
      and a private reading-progress layer.
    </p>

    <hr class="gleam" />

    <h2>Faithfulness principles</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Strict separation of voices.</strong> Our notes are clearly marked as a companion aid and are never presented as Nursî's words.</li>
      <li><strong>Not a “simplified Risale.”</strong> This is a study aid, not an easier or modernised version of the text.</li>
      <li><strong>Faithfulness over cleverness.</strong> Our summaries describe and map the text; they do not editorialise, issue rulings, or extrapolate beyond it.</li>
      <li><strong>In our own words.</strong> Summaries are written so they never reproduce a translation's wording. Anything uncertain is marked for review.</li>
      <li><strong>Qur'anic verses.</strong> Arabic is shown as-is; English meanings carry an explicit translation source.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr class="gleam" />

    <h2 id="copyright">Copyright &amp; disclaimer</h2>
    <p>
      We do not own or redistribute the Risale-i Nur text. All rights to the
      original Turkish and to its translations belong to their respective
      holders. The original Turkish remains under copyright in Turkey, and the
      English translations are separately copyrighted. We link out to the
      official source rather than reproducing any of it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Qur'anic verse meanings quoted on this site are limited quotations of
      individual verses, shown with their translation source attributed on the
      page. We do not reproduce any translation in full.
    </p>

    <h2 id="privacy">Privacy</h2>
    <p>
      No accounts, no backend, no analytics, no third-party tracking, no ads.
      Anything you save — reading progress, bookmarks and notes — is stored
      <strong>only on your device</strong>, in your browser's local storage, and
      never leaves it. You can clear all of it at any time:
    </p>
    <ResetData />
    <p class="ui muted reset-hint">
      This removes your read-status, bookmarks, notes, continue-reading and the
      15-day tracker from this browser. Your light/dark preference is kept.
    </p>

    <h2 id="license">Licensing</h2>
    <p>
      The code of this site is released under the <strong>MIT License</strong>.
      Our original companion content (summaries, outlines, glossary, structure)
      is released under <strong>CC&nbsp;BY-SA&nbsp;4.0</strong>. These licenses
      apply only to our work, not to the Risale-i Nur or its translations.
    </p>

    <h2>Corrections &amp; contributions</h2>
    <p>
      Faithfulness matters more than speed here. If you find an error in an
      outline, summary, glossary term, or an official-source link, corrections
      are welcome — see the contribution guide in the repository.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
